Subject: Recognize \p{...} / \P{...} under the /v flag (UnicodeSetsMode)

ECMA-262 specifies that `\p{<UnicodePropertyValueExpression>}` is a valid
CharacterClassEscape whenever the regex is in UnicodeMode — which is either
the `/u` flag (LRE_FLAG_UNICODE / `s->is_unicode`) or the `/v` flag
(LRE_FLAG_UNICODE_SETS / `s->unicode_sets`). QuickJS-NG's character-class
escape parser only enters the property-escape branch under `s->is_unicode`,
so under `/v` the `\p` falls through to the unknown-escape default. The
default for non-strict mode is "ignore the backslash" — which silently
turns `[\p{Default_Ignorable_Code_Point}]` into the character class
`[pDefault_Ignorable_Code_Point{}]` (literal letters from the property
name plus the braces).

Concrete user-visible regression chain: pi-tui's `visibleWidth()` uses
`/^[\p{Default_Ignorable_Code_Point}\p{Control}\p{Format}\p{Mark}\p{Surrogate}]+/v`
to strip leading non-printing chars. Under QuickJS-NG every ASCII letter
that appears in any of those property names matches the misparsed class
(t, i, n, p, g, m, u, D, k, …), so ordinary words like "settings" or
"login" are reported as zero-width and downstream padding overshoots the
viewport. The resulting wrap corrupts pi-tui's incremental redraw and
stacks menu borders. Reproduced via the pi-coding-agent browser demo and
isolated to this branch with `lnpMatch="CDFIMPS_abdefgiklmnoprtu{}"`,
i.e. the union of unique letters in the regex source.

The primary fix routes the `/v` flag through the same property-escape
branch as `/u`. `parse_unicode_property` already implements the subset
of property escapes shared by both modes (General_Category, Script,
Script_Extensions, binary properties), so the existing call site does
exactly what's needed for the property names pi-tui (and similar code)
relies on.

The secondary part stubs ECMA-262's `/v`-only "of-strings" properties
(`RGI_Emoji`, `Basic_Emoji`, `Emoji_Keycap_Sequence`, the four
`RGI_Emoji_*_Sequence` variants). These match strings of one-or-more
code points and need string-set support across the regex engine to
implement correctly — out of scope here. Pre-fix they were silently
misparsed (the same way every other `\p` was), so existing /v regexes
that referenced them compiled fine and never matched any single code
point. With the primary fix in place they would suddenly become hard
SyntaxErrors at compile time (e.g. pi-tui's `rgiEmojiRegex` fails to
load), so the stub list preserves the prior "compiles but never matches
a code point" shape until real of-strings support lands. `\P{<stub>}`
still inverts the empty range to "matches any code point" — also wrong,
but the same shape as the previous misparse and not worse.

This brings QuickJS-NG's character-class property-escape parsing in
line with ECMA-262 §22.2.1.6 (Static Semantics: CharacterValue) read
together with §22.2.2.1 (Notation: 'UnicodeMode is either +Unicode or
+UnicodeSets') for the subset of properties QuickJS already supports,
and keeps regexes referencing of-strings properties loadable.
---
diff --git a/libregexp.c b/libregexp.c
--- a/libregexp.c
+++ b/libregexp.c
@@ -570,6 +570,35 @@ static bool is_unicode_char(int c)
             (c == '_'));
 }

+/* ECMA-262 §22.2.1.6 valid-under-/v "of-strings" properties. They match
+   sequences of one-or-more code points; QuickJS-NG's regex engine only
+   tracks code-point ranges, so these are stubbed to an empty CharRange.
+   Result: \p{<of-strings>}/v compiles cleanly but never matches a code
+   point — the same observable shape that V8 produces for code points
+   outside the property's set, just not the multi-code-point sequences.
+   This keeps libraries like pi-tui (which use /^\p{RGI_Emoji}$/v for
+   width detection) loadable; emoji width then falls through to the
+   East-Asian-Width tables. A real implementation needs string-set
+   matching across the regex engine — out of scope here. */
+static bool is_unicode_strings_prop_stub(const char *name)
+{
+    static const char * const names[] = {
+        "Basic_Emoji",
+        "Emoji_Keycap_Sequence",
+        "RGI_Emoji",
+        "RGI_Emoji_Modifier_Sequence",
+        "RGI_Emoji_Flag_Sequence",
+        "RGI_Emoji_Tag_Sequence",
+        "RGI_Emoji_ZWJ_Sequence",
+    };
+    size_t i;
+    for (i = 0; i < sizeof(names) / sizeof(names[0]); i++) {
+        if (!strcmp(name, names[i]))
+            return true;
+    }
+    return false;
+}
+
 static int parse_unicode_property(REParseState *s, CharRange *cr,
                                   const uint8_t **pp, bool is_inv)
 {
@@ -640,11 +669,16 @@ static int parse_unicode_property(REParseState *s, CharRange *cr,
         if (ret < 0) {
             ret = unicode_prop(cr, name);
             if (ret) {
-                cr_free(cr);
-                if (ret == -2)
-                    goto unknown_property_name;
-                else
-                    goto out_of_memory;
+                if (ret == -2 && s->unicode_sets &&
+                    is_unicode_strings_prop_stub(name)) {
+                    /* keep cr initialized + empty: stub matches nothing */
+                } else {
+                    cr_free(cr);
+                    if (ret == -2)
+                        goto unknown_property_name;
+                    else
+                        goto out_of_memory;
+                }
             }
         }
     } else {
@@ -724,7 +758,7 @@ static int parse_unicode_property(REParseState *s, CharRange *cr,
             break;
         case 'p':
         case 'P':
-            if (s->is_unicode) {
+            if (s->is_unicode || s->unicode_sets) {
                 if (parse_unicode_property(s, cr, &p, (c == 'P')))
                     return -1;
                 c = CLASS_RANGE_BASE;
